UPDATE public.blog_posts SET
  blocks_es = '[{"id":"1f9aceb3-3b28-4743-ba23-151f87aba0e7","type":"paragraph","html":"Todas las agencias empiezan igual: un Excel con nombres en columna, proyectos en fila y una fórmula que suma horas. Funciona mientras el equipo cabe en una pantalla. Cuando no cabe, el problema no es la hoja en sí: es el tiempo que consume mantenerla viva y la facilidad con la que oculta sobrecargas."},{"id":"e4ecdfe8-76d0-4a30-be20-d3b901c30cc8","type":"paragraph","html":"Este artículo no es un «Excel vs software»: es una guía para montar la plantilla más útil posible, entender cuándo flaquea y saber qué criterio mantener si decides dar el salto a una herramienta integrada. Al final hay una plantilla .xlsx con cinco hojas listas para usar: instrucciones, equipo, proyectos, asignación semanal e insights con formato condicional y KPIs."},{"id":"2127cf00-62ab-4123-b765-11673c4ef654","type":"paragraph","html":"Si estabas comparando plantillas gratuitas de planificación de recursos, esta está pensada para uso real en agencia: no solo reparte horas, también cruza capacidad neta, pacing, coste y margen."},{"id":"c14ee797-b878-49c4-a775-c092cecb620a","type":"paragraph","html":"Si buscas las métricas que acompañan a esta plantilla, el tema se amplía en <strong>KPIs para agencias de marketing: 5 métricas que sí importan en 2026</strong>. Aquí el foco está en la estructura de la hoja, las fórmulas y el momento en que deja de compensar."},{"id":"8fe3dda6-b620-472b-ac8a-bbcf7a283620","type":"cta","text":"Descargar plantilla .xlsx","href":"/planificador-recursos","variant":"primary"},{"id":"f363f2c8-b667-48fe-b770-82cbba0a35d6","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>5 hojas, fórmulas nativas, formato condicional, desplegables y protección de celdas. Funciona en Excel y Google Sheets.</em>"},{"id":"027e15f0-93b2-47fa-8c8e-c380201c77f4","type":"toc"},{"id":"b41964c2-5300-4f65-806a-79809c91de66","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"1. Por qué el Excel es el «primer amor» de toda agencia","anchorId":"intro"},{"id":"1abc1986-1d71-44a7-bda0-f30664cd02df","type":"paragraph","html":"Coste cero, flexibilidad total y curva de aprendizaje que el equipo ya domina. Para cinco personas y cuatro clientes, una hoja bien pensada basta para ver quién está cargado y dónde hay margen. Nadie necesita justificar una licencia ni configurar permisos: abres, escribes y compartes. La cicatriz es cuando el martes llega “versión 4” por email y nadie sabe cuál es la que refleja la realidad."},{"id":"a13ef1ea-960f-4805-ab98-8493a413b08d","type":"paragraph","html":"El romance dura mientras el mantenimiento es anecdótico. Con ocho o diez personas, varios proyectos simultáneos y un par de incorporaciones recientes, el escenario cambia: alguien tiene que ser el guardián de la hoja. Actualizar quién trabaja en qué, perseguir a quien no rellena sus horas y detectar que una fórmula se descuadró hace tres semanas."},{"id":"52cbbf11-2615-417b-88f1-a8160db43acf","type":"paragraph","html":"Ese rol de guardián suele recaer en el Traffic Manager o el PM. Y ahí aparece un coste invisible: las horas que dedica a la hoja no van a gestión de cuenta ni a producción. La herramienta gratuita tiene un peaje en tiempo de gente que factura."},{"id":"44ee3c2a-81bd-4134-a7b6-71f27d95cb05","type":"callout","tone":"info","html":"Según estudios de productividad en agencias de servicios, los mandos intermedios gastan entre 3 y 6 horas semanales en tareas de reporting manual (preparar datos, reconciliar versiones, actualizar cuadros). Tiempo que no se factura ni se ve como «coste» hasta que se mide."},{"id":"7ecc5d3c-92bd-40b0-a189-44409644ba06","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"2. Capacidad bruta vs capacidad neta: la primera fórmula que importa","anchorId":"capacity"},{"id":"9bdc9475-e537-4309-8625-562a5c23e5c0","type":"paragraph","html":"Capacidad bruta es el contrato: normalmente 40 h/semana. Capacidad neta es lo que queda para trabajo de producción o cliente después de descontar reuniones recurrentes, formación, administración interna y ausencias puntuales (vacaciones, festivos, bajas). La cicatriz aparece cuando comparas “bruta vs asignada” y el equipo está agotado, pero el número sigue pareciendo verde."},{"id":"097b8c42-578d-4a1d-b5fa-d41a8af237ef","type":"paragraph","html":"La diferencia importa porque, si comparas horas asignadas contra la bruta, la utilización siempre parece baja y «hay margen» que en realidad no existe. Es el error más común en plantillas de agencia y el que más sobrecargas oculta."},{"id":"c3076b97-400f-49ae-bc8b-85be2424359a","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Ejemplo con números"},{"id":"8e0c042f-272e-46e0-b977-9a5f912abe09","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Ana tiene 32 h reales para trabajo de cliente, no 40. Si le asignas 35 h en proyectos, no está «al 87 %»: está al 109 % de su capacidad real, y eso se traduce en horas extra invisibles.</em>"},{"id":"6ea28981-0df1-4cab-adea-0136a3ec5de1","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Fórmula en la plantilla (hoja «Equipo», columna G)"},{"id":"1ac45b4c-7461-44f8-9414-eba8a769e9d2","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Es decir: Jornada − Reuniones − Admin − Ausencias. Cuatro columnas de descuento; la neta se calcula sola al rellenar las otras.</em>"},{"id":"d62d2d94-9027-404e-82aa-3c49a478b98e","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"3. Anatomía de la plantilla: cuatro hojas y cómo se conectan","anchorId":"anatomy"},{"id":"7b222e52-4156-4429-85b5-302ca83435c2","type":"paragraph","html":"La estructura profesional se apoya en cuatro hojas encadenadas (más una de instrucciones): inventario de equipo, catálogo de proyectos, cuadrante de asignación semanal y dashboard de insights. Cada una alimenta a la siguiente; si alguna falla, el resultado final pierde sentido. Lo notas cuando una hoja “no se ha tocado” y aun así cambian los KPIs… porque la fórmula estaba apuntando a otro rango."},{"id":"462606ec-155f-4768-900c-d9abc60a6913","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Hoja «Equipo» — Inventario de capacidad"},{"id":"bb18a641-45c3-47de-8ae0-9f9e365e975d","type":"paragraph","html":"Aquí defines quiénes sois y cuántas horas reales tiene cada uno. Ocho columnas: persona, rol, jornada, reuniones, admin/formación, ausencias semanales, capacidad neta (fórmula automática) y coste hora interno. La fila de totales suma jornada, reuniones, admin, ausencias y capacidad neta de todo el equipo."},{"id":"ed774148-a620-49f0-92ab-d686f0b3f510","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Clave: actualizar la columna «Ausencias semana» cuando alguien tenga festivos, vacaciones o baja. Si no se toca, el % de utilización en Insights empieza a mentir en silencio.</em>"},{"id":"ac7a3e96-49d2-4fa7-9e62-2498f44770f1","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Hoja «Proyectos» — Fee, presupuesto y margen"},{"id":"48b97ecd-52fa-4152-b527-c7bd47b456da","type":"paragraph","html":"Cada proyecto (o servicio-cliente) ocupa una fila. Tú rellenas nombre, tipo (Retainer / Proyecto / Interno con desplegable), fee mensual y horas presupuestadas al mes. Las columnas de cálculo hacen el resto:"},{"id":"ed04c296-3923-43cd-ba9d-32f9b1c879e6","type":"list","ordered":false,"items":["Horas asignadas semana: suma automática desde la hoja de Asignación (SUMIF).","Pacing (%): horas asignadas esta semana vs media semanal presupuestada (horas mes ÷ 4). Si supera el 100 % vas «por delante» del presupuesto.","Coste semana estimado: cruza horas asignadas con el coste hora de cada persona (SUMPRODUCT × VLOOKUP).","Margen mensual estimado: fee − (coste semana × 4). Si sale negativo, la celda se pinta en rojo."]},{"id":"117e8a01-ee4d-4821-b35f-0285eec0c94a","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Clave: el margen es una estimación basada en la asignación actual; no sustituye al cierre contable real, pero anticipa tendencias antes de que sea tarde.</em>"},{"id":"a07c9413-83d9-464a-81aa-cbbe43cf9846","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Hoja «Asignación» — El cuadrante semanal"},{"id":"540cfb85-52ac-4a94-a433-39ac8db6c479","type":"paragraph","html":"El cruce personas × proyectos × semana. Cada fila es un bloque de asignación: quién, en qué proyecto, qué semana, cuántas horas y una nota libre. Las columnas Persona y Proyecto tienen desplegables enlazados a las hojas Equipo y Proyectos, lo que evita errores de escritura que rompen las fórmulas SUMIF."},{"id":"703e9c31-2bff-4509-aaff-353e6af6b2ea","type":"paragraph","html":"La plantilla incluye dos semanas de datos de ejemplo (S12 y S13) con 8 personas y 6 proyectos repartidos de forma realista, más 20 filas vacías con los desplegables ya configurados para que empieces a rellenar directamente."},{"id":"c9009a53-8528-4eb6-8100-22e20a1330e5","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Clave: el nivel de granularidad. Semanas suele ser el término medio ideal en agencias; por día es demasiado fino para mantener en Excel y por mes es demasiado grueso para detectar picos.</em>"},{"id":"3c809dac-6c6b-4c93-8830-540f94301122","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Hoja «Insights» — Dashboard de alertas y KPIs"},{"id":"93be7d48-fef4-49bd-b63d-86a47845b67e","type":"paragraph","html":"Todo automático: departamento, capacidad neta, horas asignadas, horas libres, utilización (%), estado, coste semanal y número de proyectos por persona. La columna de utilización tiene formato condicional real con tres niveles de color:"},{"id":"e95d9a1b-bfd3-42fb-8384-9d93a7fb31d6","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Clave: mirar esta hoja al principio de cada semana, no al final del mes. La alerta temprana es lo que diferencia una plantilla decorativa de una operativa.</em>"},{"id":"9aa643ef-5548-4d2d-ac50-6be7071637b2","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Mockup: cuadrante semanal (ejemplo visual)</em>"},{"id":"368505e0-cc9e-4ede-9f4a-5ad53eaabcb5","type":"table","headers":["Persona","Cap. neta (h)","H. asignadas","H. libres","Utilización","Estado"],"rows":[["Ana L.","⚠️ RIESGO"],["Luis G.","⚠️ RIESGO"],["María P.","⛔ SOBRECARGA"],["Jorge N.","⚠️ RIESGO"]]},{"id":"c2dc2938-67be-45a0-9b2e-3ebf53bf02be","type":"cta","text":"Descargar plantilla con las cuatro hojas","href":"/planificador-recursos","variant":"primary"},{"id":"84a338c5-9210-42bb-98cd-c825c90d1b94","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"4. Fórmula de utilización y formato condicional","anchorId":"utilization"},{"id":"61a500b8-790b-4038-936c-23d124aef0fd","type":"paragraph","html":"La métrica central de la plantilla es la tasa de utilización: qué proporción de la capacidad neta de una persona está asignada a proyectos. La fórmula es directa:"},{"id":"646beb55-9af4-419c-9b6a-de2fff540b02","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Ejemplo con números (semana 12)"},{"id":"bf54cbe9-118f-4f8a-8283-dcce1c6891b4","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Fórmula maestra (hoja «Insights», columna F)"},{"id":"54d669ef-5ca0-4dca-aa19-f4d6cea2e299","type":"paragraph","html":"Donde D2 son las horas asignadas (calculadas con SUMIF desde Asignación) y C2 es la capacidad neta (traída de Equipo). El IFERROR evita el error #DIV/0! si la neta es cero."},{"id":"2e46448a-7f61-491c-8efd-0515d73c3dc6","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Formato condicional (tres niveles de color)"},{"id":"a9c4d4de-6a94-472c-9506-caab38317a55","type":"paragraph","html":"La plantilla aplica formato condicional nativo en la columna de utilización. Excel y Google Sheets lo interpretan directamente al abrir el archivo:"},{"id":"92c80c9f-b128-41db-9a30-4f90e2b0c15d","type":"list","ordered":false,"items":["Verde (70–90%): zona óptima, hay colchón para imprevistos.","Ámbar (> 90%): zona de riesgo, cualquier imprevisto desborda.","Rojo (≥ 100%): sobrecarga declarada, la persona ya no tiene horas."]},{"id":"8725fa87-fcbc-4466-8c3b-b05ba18187e1","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Columna «Estado» (cuatro niveles con fórmula IF anidada)"},{"id":"d3a95dd7-7f61-4077-9279-381445a245f9","type":"paragraph","html":"Cuatro estados que se leen de un vistazo. «Baja carga» no significa que la persona no trabaje; puede estar en formación o tener ausencias esa semana. El valor está en el patrón a lo largo de varias semanas."},{"id":"b7b54a6d-eb9c-4395-a31c-116b94f46d34","type":"paragraph","html":"María tiene 29 h netas (40 − 8 reuniones − 3 admin). Esta semana tiene asignadas 29 h en cuatro proyectos. Utilización: 29 / 29 = 100 %. Estado: ⛔ SOBRECARGA. No tiene ni una hora libre para un imprevisto. Si un cliente pide algo urgente, alguien va a hacer horas extra o un entregable se va a retrasar."},{"id":"9c93fa2f-8c35-48ef-8c12-bab6b64baad0","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"5. Pacing por proyecto y margen estimado","anchorId":"pacing"},{"id":"7e42cc8a-93f7-48ed-ab18-4d34373bea17","type":"paragraph","html":"La hoja Proyectos añade dos métricas que un cuadrante sencillo no suele incluir: el pacing (ritmo de consumo de horas) y el margen mensual estimado. La cicatriz es cuando el Excel te marca un buen pacing… y aun así el fee se va en horas antes de que cierre el mes."},{"id":"8f178ff2-8a67-429c-a024-956045e6231d","type":"paragraph","html":"El pacing compara las horas asignadas esta semana con lo que «debería» asignarse si repartes el presupuesto mensual de forma lineal (horas presupuestadas ÷ 4 semanas). Un pacing del 120 % significa que estás consumiendo horas un 20 % más rápido de lo presupuestado; si se mantiene, el fee se agotará antes de fin de mes."},{"id":"41b0522f-6065-4a9b-a8a5-342b39f87c22","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Ejemplo: proyecto «Marca Beta — Web»"},{"id":"c72a08d0-7073-4b68-a17c-eb3c2c751494","type":"table","headers":["Métrica","Valor"],"rows":[["Fee mensual","8.000 €"],["Horas presupuestadas / mes","100 h"],["Media semanal presupuestada","25 h (100 ÷ 4)"],["Horas asignadas esta semana","30 h"],["Pacing","120%"],["Margen mensual estimado","8.000 − (coste sem. × 4)"]]},{"id":"08089b54-d94a-449e-a9f4-b829bbd54b1b","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Si el pacing supera el 100 % dos semanas seguidas, es una señal clara de que el alcance se ha expandido o la estimación se quedó corta. El formato condicional pinta la celda en ámbar (>100 %) o rojo (>120 %) para que salte a la vista.</em>"},{"id":"4637e94e-8729-43f9-87e3-94dcbb13d51c","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"6. El «impuesto Excel»: cuánto cuesta mantener la hoja","anchorId":"excelTax"},{"id":"10b98bc9-b1b2-438e-8a3c-685fa343f42b","type":"paragraph","html":"Si un PM con coste hora de 40 € dedica 4 horas semanales a actualizar el Excel (perseguir datos, corregir fórmulas, reconciliar versiones, preparar el resumen para la reunión de carga), el coste directo es. La cicatriz: cuando el reporte consume más tiempo del que te ayuda a tomar decisiones."},{"id":"4f3727f6-9b02-4ac6-9642-38fadc454f3e","type":"paragraph","html":"No es «gratis»: es un impuesto fijo sobre el margen que no aparece en ninguna línea de coste porque nadie lo factura. Y a eso se suma lo que el PM no hace mientras alimenta la hoja: gestión de cuenta, negociación de alcance, tiempo con el equipo creativo."},{"id":"a928720f-b40b-44f7-8f3f-eb0ff661ad74","type":"paragraph","html":"La plantilla incluye este cálculo en el bloque de KPIs de la hoja Insights (4 × coste hora del PM × 52 semanas), para que el número esté visible cada vez que se abre el archivo."},{"id":"506b8410-ad2d-4bcc-badd-f8423ca2fbbb","type":"callout","tone":"info","html":"<strong>4 h × 40 €/h × 4 semanas = 640 €/mes</strong>"},{"id":"b66edd33-6391-4d0c-ad69-762012b92ecb","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Son 7.680 €/año en mantener un archivo estático. Si dos personas lo tocan, multiplica.</em>"},{"id":"a5be768f-cc89-4774-bea9-aecc62712904","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"7. Techo de cristal: tres puntos donde la hoja se rompe","anchorId":"ceiling"},{"id":"8cb6abb4-51fa-427e-80cf-fa5debadb44f","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"1. Arqueología de datos"},{"id":"6e6b2cf8-dbe1-48f7-8767-5dcce09d183d","type":"paragraph","html":"Perseguir a todo el equipo para que rellene sus horas, cuadrar versiones del archivo y descubrir que la hoja de la semana pasada no se actualizó. El dato existe, pero llegar a él cuesta más que el propio valor que aporta. La cicatriz es que el “dato clave” aparece justo después de la reunión donde ibais a decidir."},{"id":"6dd65b7a-29d6-4cc1-8cee-2c28e2f9606b","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"2. Desconexión con la realidad"},{"id":"4b66f90b-c121-446f-aa44-e372c5d006ee","type":"paragraph","html":"El Excel dice que las horas están asignadas, pero no sabe si las tareas se ejecutan ni si el margen del proyecto está bajando. Puedes tener «100 % de asignación» y descubrir al cerrar el mes que el fee se agotó en la segunda semana. No hay pacing en tiempo real: solo el que tú calcules."},{"id":"95f807ba-4d05-443f-9b33-ac0e90d1d965","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"3. Error de fórmula humano"},{"id":"4b7e4d8d-dcbd-42f4-87e8-1e3b8a712b79","type":"paragraph","html":"Una celda borrada por error, una fila que no se copió bien o un rango que se desplazó al insertar columnas. El resultado: un diseñador lleva tres semanas al 140 % de carga y nadie lo vio porque la fórmula apuntaba al rango equivocado. Cuando se detecta, el daño ya está hecho. La protección de celdas de la plantilla reduce este riesgo, pero no lo elimina del todo."},{"id":"86ee4c0d-3160-4c61-b2aa-41995f58bf78","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>Ninguno de estos problemas es del Excel como herramienta: es del flujo manual. Cualquier hoja, por bien pensada que esté, necesita que alguien la alimente puntualmente y que nadie la toque por error. En equipos pequeños el coste es asumible; al escalar, se vuelve un riesgo operativo.</strong>"},{"id":"b5a2deaf-21a0-448f-b876-0365f94bc5aa","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"8. Validación de datos y protección: cómo evitar que la hoja se rompa","anchorId":"validation"},{"id":"7bfd53b2-2d52-43c5-978a-23b2a7f18037","type":"paragraph","html":"El 80 % de los errores en una plantilla de recursos viene de dos sitios: alguien escribe un nombre con una tilde distinta y el SUMIF no cruza, o alguien borra una fórmula sin querer. La plantilla incluye dos mecanismos para minimizar ambos. Lo sientes cuando alguien “solo mira” una celda y, sin avisar, rompe el cálculo del margen."},{"id":"cc157204-f787-4317-96e5-e11318fe3eef","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Desplegables (data validation)"},{"id":"271502ac-43cc-47e6-993d-a5cc90a67aa7","type":"paragraph","html":"Las columnas «Persona» y «Proyecto» de la hoja Asignación tienen listas desplegables enlazadas a los nombres de Equipo y Proyectos. Al hacer clic en la celda aparece la flechita y se selecciona en lugar de escribir. Esto garantiza que el nombre coincida carácter por carácter con la hoja de origen, y que SUMIF, VLOOKUP y COUNTIF funcionen."},{"id":"90ceb058-82ec-4b0e-bd98-b5d0dfc0eb87","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Si necesitas añadir una persona o proyecto nuevo, añádelo primero en la hoja correspondiente y luego actualiza la lista del desplegable (Datos → Validación de datos).</em>"},{"id":"c76774b3-3ac7-42a2-9c35-d9083f8f7025","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Protección de celdas"},{"id":"c83c88bb-5da1-4bcc-9701-02231f9462d3","type":"paragraph","html":"Todas las celdas con fórmula (Capacidad neta, Utilización, Estado, Margen, KPIs…) están protegidas: si intentas escribir encima, Excel te avisa. Las celdas de entrada (nombre, horas, notas) quedan libres. La protección se puede desactivar sin contraseña (Revisar → Desproteger hoja) si necesitas ajustar algo, pero mientras esté activa evita el borrado accidental."},{"id":"cb00454d-3608-408f-b407-9e6b021a4ed7","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>En Google Sheets, al importar el .xlsx la protección se convierte en «rangos protegidos» con el mismo efecto.</em>"},{"id":"75b35887-453f-4cfe-9ba1-3dbf4298bd85","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"9. Cómo escalar la plantilla semana a semana","anchorId":"scale"},{"id":"751a79cc-b3c3-464b-8e75-92c26233e990","type":"paragraph","html":"La plantilla viene con dos semanas de ejemplo (S12 y S13). Para añadir una nueva semana, el proceso es:"},{"id":"adc22176-b019-4a01-936e-8b490073d5ec","type":"list","ordered":true,"items":["Hoja Equipo: revisar la columna «Ausencias semana». Si alguien tiene vacaciones o un festivo, actualizar las horas. La capacidad neta se recalcula sola.","Hoja Asignación: añadir filas nuevas para la semana siguiente. Usa los desplegables de Persona y Proyecto. Puedes copiar las filas de la semana anterior y cambiar la columna «Semana» y las horas.","Hoja Insights: no tocar nada. Las fórmulas SUMIF suman todas las filas de Asignación independientemente de la semana, así que el dashboard se actualiza solo."]},{"id":"5a324cb4-e65c-4108-af83-8cc44579717a","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Truco: filtrar por semana"},{"id":"7e18c894-b0e4-42a6-8a46-4a3202894040","type":"paragraph","html":"Todas las hojas de datos tienen autofiltros activados. En Asignación puedes filtrar por la columna «Semana» para ver solo la semana actual. En Insights puedes filtrar por departamento para revisar la carga de un equipo concreto. Los totales de la plantilla suman el rango completo, pero el filtro visual te permite centrarte en lo que importa en cada reunión."},{"id":"d6f22e1e-4abb-4ccf-a0df-389ba7c7b5e3","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Limitación: como Insights suma todas las semanas, si dejas las filas antiguas de Asignación, las horas acumuladas crecen semana tras semana. Para un dashboard «solo esta semana», filtra o borra las filas de semanas anteriores. Es una de las fricciones del modelo manual que una herramienta integrada resuelve automáticamente.</em>"},{"id":"f5492cea-df02-48bd-ac1e-e27a931bd751","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"10. Google Sheets vs Excel: ¿cambia algo?","anchorId":"sheetsVsExcel"},{"id":"628bab5a-a0a1-4106-8d1f-560566f017ed","type":"paragraph","html":"La plantilla funciona en los dos; las fórmulas son compatibles. La diferencia relevante es operativa:"},{"id":"369dec0f-2fc0-4a70-b281-47eb0f84c14f","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>La conclusión: da igual el formato. El techo está en el modelo manual, no en si abres .xlsx o lo importas en Drive.</strong>"},{"id":"ab5c9a4f-471b-4954-8120-27b2bfb9a1e5","type":"list","ordered":false,"items":["Colaboración en tiempo real: Sheets permite que varias personas editen a la vez, lo que reduce el problema de «versión 3 o versión 4». Pero no elimina el riesgo de pisarse celdas ni de romper una fórmula sin querer.","Historial de cambios: Sheets guarda versiones automáticamente. Excel solo si usas OneDrive/SharePoint. En la práctica, ambos cubren el caso de «quién rompió la fila 12».","Desplegables y protección: al importar el .xlsx en Google Sheets, los desplegables se convierten en validación de datos nativa y la protección en rangos protegidos. No hay que reconfigurar nada.","Rendimiento: con muchas filas y fórmulas cruzadas, Excel local suele ir más fluido que Sheets en el navegador. Para plantillas de 5–30 personas, la diferencia es despreciable."]},{"id":"0b20c8a6-1a0e-451d-b1e6-21d31bbf8e60","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"11. Evolución: de rellenar celdas a planificación pasiva","anchorId":"evolution"},{"id":"af609e55-509c-4f7b-a7bf-f1326e30ee14","type":"paragraph","html":"La lógica que acabas de estructurar —capacidad neta, cuadrante de asignación, pacing, margen y utilización— es exactamente la misma que usa un sistema integrado. La diferencia es quién la mantiene: tú a mano o la herramienta de forma pasiva."},{"id":"97308205-ff4a-4b6c-9495-bb7f267766d8","type":"paragraph","html":"En Taimbox, mueves bloques en el planificador por horas. Los informes de utilización, carga por departamento y margen por proyecto se alimentan de ese movimiento sin que alguien reimporte números cada lunes. El criterio es el tuyo; la ejecución del dato deja de depender de copiar y pegar."},{"id":"64202e6c-eb35-4362-8d8c-9f6109c51f8d","type":"paragraph","html":"No es «tirar el Excel» el primer día: es llevar la plantilla mental (y las fórmulas) a un sitio donde el dato no se descuadra. La evolución natural cuando el equipo ya no cabe en filas y columnas compartidas."},{"id":"4c6cf4d4-2b03-46ca-8fe1-2927d437d04b","type":"callout","tone":"highlight","html":"Planificación pasiva: tú planificas; Taimbox calcula utilización, margen y capacidad en segundo plano. Las métricas que antes montabas a mano nacen de la forma en que trabajáis, sin reconciliar hojas.<br/><em>Los reportes de rentabilidad y el planificador de recursos detallan el enfoque en sus landings.</em>"},{"id":"c68ba093-cf9c-4f37-b06a-03af81c4c1ae","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Preguntas frecuentes","anchorId":"preguntas-frecuentes"},{"id":"0a9aff6a-0f41-4751-b99c-a3c941e4ef7b","type":"faq","items":[{"q":"¿Necesito macros o VBA para que funcione la plantilla?","a":"No. Solo usa fórmulas estándar (SUMA, SI, SUMIF, VLOOKUP, SUMPRODUCT, COUNTIF) y formato condicional nativo. Funciona en Excel, LibreOffice y Google Sheets sin necesidad de habilitar macros."},{"q":"¿Cada cuánto hay que actualizar la plantilla?","a":"Lo ideal es revisarla al inicio de cada semana (o al final de la anterior): ajustar ausencias en Equipo y añadir las asignaciones de la nueva semana. La frecuencia semanal da tiempo a reaccionar antes de que una sobrecarga se convierta en crisis."},{"q":"¿A partir de cuántas personas deja de ser práctico el Excel?","a":"No hay un número mágico; depende más del ritmo de cambios (proyectos nuevos, rotaciones) que del tamaño. En la práctica, muchas agencias notan la fricción entre 8 y 15 personas con múltiples proyectos simultáneos: ahí el mantenimiento semanal empieza a no compensar."},{"q":"¿Puedo usar esta plantilla junto a un tablero Kanban (Trello, Asana…)?","a":"Sí: el Kanban gestiona el flujo de tareas; la plantilla de recursos gestiona horas y capacidad. Se complementan: el tablero dice «qué se está haciendo» y la plantilla dice «quién tiene horas libres para hacerlo»."},{"q":"¿Qué rango de utilización es «sano» en una agencia?","a":"Orientativo: 70–85 % sobre capacidad neta en muchas agencias de servicios. Por debajo puede indicar falta de pipeline; por encima del 90 % empieza el riesgo de quemazo y errores. El mix de negocio (retainers, proyectos puntuales, I+D interna) cambia el objetivo."},{"q":"¿El pacing tiene en cuenta que no todos los meses duran lo mismo?","a":"La fórmula divide las horas presupuestadas entre 4 semanas como aproximación. En meses de 5 semanas laborales, el pacing real será ligeramente inferior al mostrado. Para la mayoría de agencias la aproximación es suficiente; si necesitas precisión al día, un sistema integrado lo resuelve mejor."},{"q":"¿Cómo actualizo los desplegables si añado una persona o proyecto nuevo?","a":"En Excel: ve a la hoja Asignación, selecciona la columna con el desplegable, Datos → Validación de datos, y amplía la lista. En Google Sheets: clic en la celda, icono de desplegable, editar lista. Los nombres deben coincidir exactamente con las hojas Equipo o Proyectos."}]},{"id":"7fc58ddb-c05e-4ec2-9d9e-4c1db4e567bd","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Resumen: lo que cambia con una plantilla bien hecha","anchorId":"resumen"},{"id":"a7414e41-038c-47e1-88c1-c02bfd6bc6c8","type":"paragraph","html":"La diferencia entre una agencia que «cree que va bien» y una que sabe que va bien suele estar en unas pocas columnas de un Excel: capacidad neta, horas asignadas, utilización, pacing y margen. No es rocket science: es disciplina de datos, desplegables para no romper nada, protección para no borrar lo importante y revisión semanal."},{"id":"0f0705bc-c0ed-44f8-812a-17ee76d6a243","type":"paragraph","html":"Cuando esa disciplina ya no escala con la hoja, la misma lógica puede vivir en una herramienta que actualiza los números de forma pasiva. El criterio que acabas de aprender no caduca; el soporte donde lo aplicas, sí puede evolucionar."},{"id":"bf05e688-ef0d-49f0-b786-84d1a69a79db","type":"paragraph","html":"Los KPIs que acompañan a esta plantilla —utilización, pacing, estimado vs real— están desarrollados enKPIs para agencias de marketing. La gestión del tiempo que evita que las tareas se expandan sin control aparece enLey de Parkinsonytimeboxing. Y la visión global de cronograma + presupuesto + equipo se detalla enplanificación de proyectos."},{"id":"fef4e792-223c-4658-9531-60e062b5e74a","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"La plantilla es el primer paso; el planificador es el siguiente","anchorId":"cta-final"},{"id":"336b3477-922a-4823-8703-a17ef6013774","type":"paragraph","html":"Capacidad, asignación, pacing y utilización sin mantener la hoja a mano. Taimbox se puede explorar sin compromiso."},{"id":"768c61af-8541-4cbf-8a2e-1f0a73fc94cf","type":"cta","text":"Cómo Taimbox automatiza tu plantilla","href":"/planificador-recursos","variant":"primary"},{"id":"6d5c441c-149c-4133-adc2-2ae8d86bfe01","type":"cta","text":"Descargar plantilla .xlsx","href":"/reportes-rentabilidad","variant":"secondary"},{"id":"336c3b6c-0b81-497a-8f25-7c052e77667c","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Escrito por el equipo de Taimbox — Gestión de recursos y rentabilidad para agencias.</em>"},{"id":"a2eb74c0-9382-47bf-8ef2-beecd32c89d4","type":"relatedPost","slug":"planificacion-proyectos-cronograma-recursos"}]'::jsonb,
  blocks_en = '[{"id":"ded2140f-3c51-4e3d-ac58-b86c75359ae3","type":"paragraph","html":"Every agency starts the same way: an Excel file with names in columns, projects in rows, and a formula summing hours. It works while the team still fits on one screen. Once it does not, the problem is not the sheet itself: it is the time it takes to keep it alive and how easily it hides overloads."},{"id":"9e3a98bf-97fa-4751-9448-5d58bcc258c6","type":"paragraph","html":"This article is not an “Excel vs. software” pitch: it is a guide to build the most useful template you can, understand where it starts to fail, and know which criteria to keep if you later move to an integrated tool. At the end you will find an .xlsx template with five sheets ready to use: instructions, team, projects, weekly allocation, and insights with conditional formatting and KPIs."},{"id":"1deacddc-bde4-4421-ae78-165157a72e44","type":"paragraph","html":"If you have been comparing free resource‑planning templates, this one is designed for real agency use: it does not just distribute hours; it also crosses net capacity, pacing, cost, and margin."},{"id":"c6603ca4-6d16-448b-8d87-1bc59adb51a4","type":"paragraph","html":"If you are looking for the metrics that go with this template, we go deeper in <strong>KPIs for marketing agencies: 5 metrics that really matter in 2026</strong>. Here the focus is on the sheet structure, the formulas, and the moment when it stops being worth the effort."},{"id":"9ba181ee-153b-4f8b-91c2-b820dc2006b6","type":"cta","text":".xlsx template download","href":"/planificador-recursos","variant":"primary"},{"id":"08410307-2e87-466d-bd56-f6042f5ddf64","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>5 sheets, native formulas, conditional formatting, dropdowns, and cell protection. Works in Excel and Google Sheets.</em>"},{"id":"ed6d4d81-3a9b-4329-b7d9-c120b77cc788","type":"toc"},{"id":"255de010-7ed6-401a-a12e-12161e368146","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"1. Why Excel is every agency’s “first love”","anchorId":"intro"},{"id":"dd3695af-25be-4c5c-b400-a2128af5bab8","type":"paragraph","html":"Zero cost, total flexibility, and a learning curve the team already mastered. For five people and four clients, a well‑designed sheet is enough to see who is loaded and where there is slack. Nobody has to justify a licence or set up permissions: you open, type, and share. The scar is when “version 4” arrives by email on Tuesday and nobody knows which one reflects reality."},{"id":"c99b2802-52a9-4ce6-bb27-a2c3727e750f","type":"paragraph","html":"The romance lasts as long as maintenance is anecdotal. With eight or ten people, several simultaneous projects, and a couple of recent hires, the picture changes: someone has to become the sheet’s gatekeeper. Updating who is working on what, chasing those who do not log their hours, and spotting that a formula drifted three weeks ago."},{"id":"9cff03f0-cc09-4d05-9a56-302919be096d","type":"paragraph","html":"That gatekeeper role usually lands on the traffic manager or PM. And there you get an invisible cost: the hours they spend on the sheet do not go to account management or production. The “free” tool charges a toll in billable people’s time."},{"id":"8c17537b-7b3e-4ab6-a214-028b9474b484","type":"callout","tone":"info","html":"In productivity studies on service agencies, middle managers spend between 3 and 6 hours a week on manual reporting (preparing data, reconciling versions, updating dashboards). Time that is neither billed nor seen as a “cost” until you measure it."},{"id":"8abfda67-4fd1-4156-af86-3bfc71e7d2d4","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"2. Gross vs. net capacity: the first formula that matters","anchorId":"capacity"},{"id":"915a4bb9-23c6-4df4-aced-a0f3cf25f848","type":"paragraph","html":"Gross capacity is the contract: usually 40 h/week. Net capacity is what is left for client or production work after subtracting recurring meetings, training, internal admin, and one‑off absences (vacations, holidays, sick leave). The scar appears when you compare “gross vs. assigned”, the team is exhausted, and the number still looks comfortably green."},{"id":"b3bb0b54-2257-479f-8440-daa8d457ad38","type":"paragraph","html":"The difference matters because if you compare assigned hours against gross capacity, utilization always looks low and “there is room” that in reality does not exist. It is the most common error in agency templates and the one that hides the most overload."},{"id":"697b29ba-15ab-4c13-b5df-267ede966511","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Example with numbers"},{"id":"cc5bb921-0b62-4187-a5e4-a683e12ea97a","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Ana has 32 real hours for client work, not 40. If you assign her 35 project hours, she is not “at 87%”: she is at 109% of her real capacity, and that turns into invisible overtime.</em>"},{"id":"bd745c9b-af0f-4774-a472-bce30855fe81","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Template formula (\"Team\" sheet, column G)"},{"id":"7c3e4fa4-97ed-4cfe-b54c-177085b3a1ad","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>In other words: Working hours − Meetings − Admin − Absences. Four subtraction columns; net capacity updates automatically as you fill in the others.</em>"},{"id":"4599839f-2d69-4633-ac87-a588c79550ed","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"3. Template anatomy: four sheets and how they connect","anchorId":"anatomy"},{"id":"0f3906de-b09f-4358-8c99-f9f4eec5d6d0","type":"paragraph","html":"A professional structure rests on four linked sheets (plus one with instructions): team inventory, project catalog, weekly allocation grid, and insights dashboard. Each feeds the next; if one fails, the final picture stops making sense. You notice it when a sheet “has not been touched” and the KPIs still change… because a formula was pointing at the wrong range."},{"id":"22bc5c57-851c-404d-a0c5-a7aa45b19122","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"\"Team\" sheet — Capacity inventory"},{"id":"5bcd5dcc-de6b-41cc-bdfb-f2fc59d51fcb","type":"paragraph","html":"Here you define who you are and how many real hours each person has. Eight columns: person, role, working hours, meetings, admin/training, weekly absences, net capacity (automatic formula), and internal hourly cost. The totals row sums working hours, meetings, admin, absences, and net capacity for the whole team."},{"id":"47d47ae6-dcbf-46c6-a6d4-1c6a6984d344","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Key: keep the “Weekly absences” column up to date when someone has holidays or time off. If it is ignored, the utilization % in Insights starts lying quietly.</em>"},{"id":"9a840203-f490-4d97-bf86-3e84176f2bca","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"\"Projects\" sheet — Fee, budget, and margin"},{"id":"fc693237-9729-4bcc-9f96-f78dce3bd05d","type":"paragraph","html":"Each project (or client‑service combo) takes one row. You fill in name, type (Retainer / Project / Internal via dropdown), monthly fee, and budgeted monthly hours. The calculation columns do the rest:"},{"id":"e24c9b65-7711-4938-9fbd-bc9ffbb3d46f","type":"list","ordered":false,"items":["Weekly hours assigned: automatic sum from the Allocation sheet (SUMIF).","Pacing (%): hours assigned this week vs. average weekly budget (monthly hours ÷ 4). If it goes over 100%, you are running ahead of budget.","Estimated weekly cost: crosses assigned hours with each person’s hourly cost (SUMPRODUCT × VLOOKUP).","Estimated monthly margin: fee − (weekly cost × 4). If it is negative, the cell turns red."]},{"id":"e1fe0f32-3a61-4ff5-b727-579990b5802d","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Key: margin is an estimate based on current allocation; it does not replace the actual accounting close, but it flags trend changes before it is too late.</em>"},{"id":"e966ec06-592a-49f4-bb08-6a7d9d36e39d","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"\"Allocation\" sheet — The weekly grid"},{"id":"04a0fd90-37b0-4a28-9e1f-e5b6d8a04950","type":"paragraph","html":"The cross between people × projects × week. Each row is an allocation block: who, on which project, which week, how many hours, and a free‑text note. The Person and Project columns use dropdowns linked to the Team and Projects sheets, which prevents typos that would break SUMIF formulas."},{"id":"e1b98221-ecc0-4c93-8ef9-1a8f94126d34","type":"paragraph","html":"The template includes two weeks of sample data (W12 and W13) with 8 people and 6 projects distributed in a realistic way, plus 20 empty rows with dropdowns already configured so you can start filling them in right away."},{"id":"68549257-1273-4458-8d18-83b14f8e4e0a","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Key: the granularity level. Weeks tend to be the sweet spot in agencies; days are too fine‑grained to maintain in Excel and months are too coarse to spot spikes.</em>"},{"id":"b0b7319b-b1ef-4dec-bb42-2cc117e3f485","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"\"Insights\" sheet — Alerts and KPI dashboard"},{"id":"6fb7d5c0-5bf1-4ee0-b58d-3b7c2d5c588e","type":"paragraph","html":"Everything is automatic: department, net capacity, assigned hours, free hours, utilization (%), status, weekly cost, and number of projects per person. The utilization column uses real conditional formatting with three colour levels:"},{"id":"dce3d21c-7ba1-4617-89e2-d53ef27be1f8","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Key: look at this sheet at the start of each week, not at the end of the month. Early alerts are what separate a decorative template from an operational one.</em>"},{"id":"ba1bd481-5abf-4a54-b098-d52d91a77bea","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Mock‑up: weekly grid (visual example)</em>"},{"id":"2849c56c-71c0-430b-bcc3-42f576ae1961","type":"table","headers":["Person","Net cap. (h)","Assigned h.","Free h.","Utilization","Status"],"rows":[["Ana L.","⚠️ AT RISK"],["Luis G.","⚠️ AT RISK"],["María P.","⛔ OVERLOADED"],["Jorge N.","⚠️ AT RISK"]]},{"id":"f07b35f2-9874-44d5-a2cd-85a2685c3c23","type":"cta","text":"Download template with all four sheets","href":"/planificador-recursos","variant":"primary"},{"id":"d877a180-21c0-48aa-86ea-255fda20a0ba","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"4. Utilization formula and conditional formatting","anchorId":"utilization"},{"id":"e1c0ea6a-b115-4f75-b9c3-00a31c7ef448","type":"paragraph","html":"The central metric in the template is the utilization rate: what share of a person’s net capacity is assigned to projects. The formula is straightforward:"},{"id":"26534164-2e7a-4379-bb55-9c230b88dc0c","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Worked example (week 12)"},{"id":"77907ac1-184b-4c61-baff-75d229e1493a","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Master formula (\"Insights\" sheet, column F)"},{"id":"cfe8118c-4fc7-4428-a82b-4ad66cfa98c8","type":"paragraph","html":"Where D2 is assigned hours (calculated with SUMIF from Allocation) and C2 is net capacity (brought in from Team). IFERROR avoids #DIV/0! when net capacity is zero."},{"id":"deca2499-baa5-420d-a1ae-2d77c05a2857","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Conditional formatting (three colour levels)"},{"id":"3f48ba4e-94ac-4c1a-a65b-c9be201f563d","type":"paragraph","html":"The template applies native conditional formatting to the utilization column. Excel and Google Sheets both interpret it out of the box:"},{"id":"f6970038-bcdf-4e06-aed7-410437299911","type":"list","ordered":false,"items":["Green (70–90%): sweet spot, there is still buffer for surprises.","Amber (> 90%): risk zone, any surprise will overflow capacity.","Red (≥ 100%): declared overload, the person has no hours left."]},{"id":"137a265d-3144-409e-9b20-6f802b5707a8","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"\"Status\" column (four levels with nested IF formula)"},{"id":"563758e8-2df7-4ac6-889e-6dae8743f4de","type":"paragraph","html":"Four states you can read at a glance. “Under‑loaded” does not mean the person is not working; they might be in training or have absences that week. The value is in the pattern across several weeks."},{"id":"ff9d9a4a-6490-4a09-b801-f3bcdfbfef51","type":"paragraph","html":"María has 29 net hours (40 − 8 meetings − 3 admin). This week she has 29 hours assigned across four projects. Utilization: 29 / 29 = 100%. Status: ⛔ OVERLOADED. She has no free hour for anything unexpected. If a client demands something urgent, someone will do unpaid overtime or a deliverable will slip."},{"id":"a875e9b2-9066-4c76-a2a4-8980c182d139","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"5. Project pacing and estimated margin","anchorId":"pacing"},{"id":"7369e99d-dac7-486e-b4a4-585342aba253","type":"paragraph","html":"The Projects sheet adds two metrics a simple grid usually lacks: pacing (the rate at which you are burning hours) and estimated monthly margin. The scar is when Excel tells you pacing is fine… and the fee is still gone in hours before the month is over."},{"id":"9820a0af-f83c-400c-b38e-9bf4c2409eca","type":"paragraph","html":"Pacing compares hours assigned this week with what “should” be assigned if you spread the monthly budget evenly (budgeted hours ÷ 4 weeks). A pacing of 120% means you are burning hours 20% faster than planned; if that continues, the fee will run out before month‑end."},{"id":"d3a55c01-13c0-4816-8df2-c049bbcedccf","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Example: “Brand Beta — Website” project"},{"id":"ef3d4469-78c2-427f-aa97-b49cd8f02041","type":"table","headers":["Metric","Value"],"rows":[["Monthly fee","€8,000"],["Budgeted hours / month","100 h"],["Budgeted weekly average","25 h (100 ÷ 4)"],["Hours assigned this week","30 h"],["Pacing","120%"],["Estimated monthly margin","8,000 − (weekly cost × 4)"]]},{"id":"4d4694df-1061-4368-bf2e-e5dd401a32c7","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>If pacing stays above 100% for two weeks in a row, it is a clear sign that scope has expanded or the estimate was too low. Conditional formatting paints the cell amber (>100%) or red (>120%) so it stands out.</em>"},{"id":"6efea021-decd-4f5a-85fc-8505074c2327","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"6. The \"Excel tax\": how much it costs to maintain the sheet","anchorId":"excelTax"},{"id":"ac5ae1c7-356c-41a7-96ca-9b610e2dc45c","type":"paragraph","html":"If a PM with an hourly cost of €40 spends 4 hours a week updating the Excel (chasing data, fixing formulas, reconciling versions, preparing the summary for the workload meeting), the direct cost is. The scar: when reporting takes more time than the decisions it is supposed to support."},{"id":"42fb7e56-95d1-49fa-baaf-dcf61cf6e63a","type":"paragraph","html":"It is not “free”: it is a fixed tax on margin that never shows up on any cost line because nobody bills it. On top of that you have what the PM is not doing while feeding the sheet: account management, scope negotiation, time with the creative team."},{"id":"12ae8f5d-82fb-4a81-95fd-e0e3e7c17bc2","type":"paragraph","html":"The template includes this calculation in the Insights KPI block (4 × PM hourly cost × 52 weeks) so the number is visible every time the file is opened."},{"id":"c635647e-0e41-4813-be1d-90ebc255523f","type":"callout","tone":"info","html":"<strong>4 h × €40/h × 4 weeks = €640/month</strong>"},{"id":"4574c078-9417-481f-84da-7d281933c9ad","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>That is €7,680/year to keep a static file alive. If two people touch it regularly, multiply.</em>"},{"id":"8bde0ef9-2475-48d9-b77b-24a0da4b7cc7","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"7. Glass ceiling: three points where the sheet breaks","anchorId":"ceiling"},{"id":"1fc9ae0b-ad81-4b43-aadf-cf295b068088","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"1. Data archaeology"},{"id":"16516f68-cb73-4b98-99b8-6e1addae6a0b","type":"paragraph","html":"Chasing the whole team to fill in hours, reconciling file versions, and discovering that last week’s sheet never got updated. The data exists, but getting to it costs more than the value it provides. The scar is when the “key number” shows up right after the meeting where you needed it most."},{"id":"dbead24e-16ef-4e28-9fca-f957133ff20a","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"2. Disconnect from reality"},{"id":"a47dff13-59cb-47e8-b0c9-c8cbdf6bbb2d","type":"paragraph","html":"Excel says hours are assigned, but it has no idea whether tasks are executed or whether project margin is sliding. You can have “100% allocation” and still discover at month‑end that the fee was burned by week two. There is no real‑time pacing, only whatever you manually calculate."},{"id":"fe8335c5-c2fa-4054-92ae-be706d1ad0be","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"3. Human formula error"},{"id":"742314bc-87c2-4f9d-a12a-3118f039fbff","type":"paragraph","html":"A cell deleted by mistake, a row copied poorly, or a range shifted when inserting columns. The result: a designer has been at 140% load for three weeks and nobody saw it because the formula was pointing at the wrong range. By the time you catch it, the damage is done. Cell protection in the template reduces this risk but does not eliminate it entirely."},{"id":"330d09c9-ff27-4426-aac2-ec59413c37e4","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>None of these problems are Excel’s fault as a tool; they are symptoms of a manual flow. Any sheet, no matter how well‑designed, needs someone feeding it on time and nobody breaking it by mistake. In small teams the cost is manageable; as you scale, it becomes an operational risk.</strong>"},{"id":"1d4ac067-7e3e-4c15-b43c-873c6b0f10c8","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"8. Data validation and protection: how not to break the sheet","anchorId":"validation"},{"id":"1a88c8ac-71e8-42e2-87e8-467308c481d1","type":"paragraph","html":"Roughly 80% of errors in a resource template come from two places: someone types a name with a different accent so SUMIF does not match, or someone deletes a formula by accident. The template includes two mechanisms to reduce both. You feel it when someone “just looks” at a cell and silently breaks the margin calculation."},{"id":"5f7732e2-ed39-4954-af70-0e53a2299440","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Dropdowns (data validation)"},{"id":"503f51d5-5cbb-45bf-94e4-a6fbb4a3bb65","type":"paragraph","html":"The \"Person\" and \"Project\" columns in the Allocation sheet use dropdown lists linked to the names in the Team and Projects sheets. When you click a cell, a little arrow appears and you pick from the list instead of typing. This guarantees the name matches the source sheet character for character so SUMIF, VLOOKUP, and COUNTIF all work."},{"id":"250ac7e6-6980-41a6-83e6-d40207224fd1","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>If you need to add a new person or project, add it to the relevant sheet first and then extend the dropdown list range (Data → Data validation).</em>"},{"id":"6e2711ac-60e7-400b-b280-256d066b77ae","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Cell protection"},{"id":"abb4b730-e8d1-4731-8ab4-a0980eb83d7d","type":"paragraph","html":"All formula cells (Net capacity, Utilization, Status, Margin, KPIs…) are protected: if you try to type over them, Excel warns you. Input cells (name, hours, notes) remain unlocked. You can turn protection off without a password (Review → Unprotect sheet) if you need to adjust something, but while it is on it prevents accidental deletion."},{"id":"737d0cb1-b149-4474-95fb-2c9dfd934b08","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>In Google Sheets, when you import the .xlsx file, protection becomes native \"protected ranges\" with the same effect.</em>"},{"id":"4f671df8-ac00-4f63-84fa-490a1b11f6d4","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"9. How to scale the template week by week","anchorId":"scale"},{"id":"2069519e-86f6-470e-956b-f86140d05d8c","type":"paragraph","html":"The template ships with two example weeks (W12 and W13). To add a new week, the process is:"},{"id":"b01fc29d-6d1b-427f-94ac-584c76280e01","type":"list","ordered":true,"items":["\"Team\" sheet: review the \"Weekly absences\" column. If someone has holidays or a bank holiday, update their hours. Net capacity recalculates automatically.","\"Allocation\" sheet: add new rows for the following week. Use the Person and Project dropdowns. You can copy rows from the previous week and change the \"Week\" column and hours.","\"Insights\" sheet: do not touch anything. SUMIF formulas add up all Allocation rows regardless of week, so the dashboard updates itself."]},{"id":"4ebab701-2218-4ace-88e6-bbd5999bc62a","type":"heading","level":3,"text":"Tip: filter by week"},{"id":"317aeec5-1a39-4a09-9c7f-cfde1deb7cd1","type":"paragraph","html":"All data sheets have filters enabled. In Allocation you can filter by the \"Week\" column to see only the current week. In Insights you can filter by department to review a specific team’s load. Template totals always sum the full range, but visual filters let you focus on what matters for each meeting."},{"id":"e9715147-6292-4e08-8d02-9eb5261d10df","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Limitation: because Insights sums all weeks, if you leave old Allocation rows in place, accumulated hours will grow week after week. For a \"this week only\" dashboard, filter or delete old week rows. This is one of the frictions of a manual model that an integrated tool solves automatically.</em>"},{"id":"81b0946e-79d9-40e5-b36f-8fecf24fa41a","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"10. Google Sheets vs. Excel: does anything change?","anchorId":"sheetsVsExcel"},{"id":"a41c71b4-f09b-4895-a2cc-e1962ab67249","type":"paragraph","html":"The template works in both; the formulas are compatible. The meaningful difference is operational:"},{"id":"e4380f66-29ac-466c-83fd-20d28d4b0d9f","type":"paragraph","html":"<strong>Bottom line: the file format does not matter. The ceiling is the manual model, not whether you open .xlsx locally or import it into Drive.</strong>"},{"id":"4460899e-a91a-43a2-b358-c9faad6dc13f","type":"list","ordered":false,"items":["Real‑time collaboration: Sheets lets several people edit at once, which reduces the “v3 or v4?” problem. It does not, however, remove the risk of overwriting cells or breaking a formula by mistake.","Change history: Sheets saves versions automatically. Excel does too if you use OneDrive/SharePoint. In practice both cover the “who broke row 12?” case.","Dropdowns and protection: when you import the .xlsx into Google Sheets, dropdowns become native data‑validation lists and protection becomes protected ranges. No need to reconfigure anything.","Performance: with many rows and cross formulas, local Excel is usually smoother than Sheets in the browser. For templates covering 5–30 people, the difference is negligible."]},{"id":"60022644-d646-4896-8cbf-ba7e2539483c","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"11. Evolution: from filling cells to passive planning","anchorId":"evolution"},{"id":"b33acc8d-e02e-473c-a8b2-63d42acd995d","type":"paragraph","html":"The logic you have just structured — net capacity, allocation grid, pacing, margin, and utilization — is exactly the same logic an integrated system uses. The difference is who maintains it: you by hand, or the tool in the background."},{"id":"268dbcc9-2f08-4685-86af-e5cc5816f51f","type":"paragraph","html":"In Taimbox, you drag blocks in the hourly planner. Utilization reports, department‑level workload, and project‑level margin all flow from that movement without someone re‑importing numbers every Monday. The criteria are yours; the data‑crunching stops depending on copy‑paste."},{"id":"f10031a6-1b20-4624-8141-27c99190268d","type":"paragraph","html":"This is not about “throwing Excel away” on day one: it is about moving the mental template (and the formulas) into a place where the data does not drift. The natural evolution once the team no longer fits comfortably in shared rows and columns."},{"id":"a76299d2-8831-4b1d-a767-6192ed3e3849","type":"callout","tone":"highlight","html":"Passive planning: you plan; Taimbox calculates utilization, margin, and capacity in the background. The metrics you used to build manually now emerge from how you actually work, without reconciling sheets.<br/><em>The profitability reports and the resource planner each have their own landing pages that go into the details.</em>"},{"id":"7c620fbb-4ecb-4056-97d7-bfda46fd248c","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Frequently asked questions","anchorId":"preguntas-frecuentes"},{"id":"13fa52b3-da55-47b5-8d13-b067f50930c7","type":"faq","items":[{"q":"Do I need macros or VBA for the template to work?","a":"No. It only uses standard formulas (SUM, IF, SUMIF, VLOOKUP, SUMPRODUCT, COUNTIF) and native conditional formatting. It works in Excel, LibreOffice, and Google Sheets without enabling macros."},{"q":"How often do I need to update the template?","a":"Ideally at the start of each week (or the end of the previous one): adjust absences in the Team sheet and add allocations for the new week. Weekly cadence gives you time to react before overload turns into a crisis."},{"q":"From how many people does Excel stop being practical?","a":"There is no magic number; it depends more on the pace of change (new projects, staff changes) than on headcount. In practice many agencies feel the friction between roughly 8 and 15 people with several parallel projects: from that point on, weekly maintenance stops paying off."},{"q":"Can I use this template alongside a Kanban board (Trello, Asana…)?","a":"Yes. The board manages the flow of tasks; the resource template manages hours and capacity. They complement each other: the board tells you what is being worked on and the template tells you who has hours left to do it."},{"q":"What utilization range is “healthy” in an agency?","a":"As a rough guide, 70–85% of net capacity in many service agencies. Below that, you may have pipeline issues; above 90% you start to see burnout and errors. The ideal point depends on your mix of work (retainers, one‑off projects, internal R&D)."},{"q":"Does pacing account for months having different lengths?","a":"The formula divides budgeted hours by 4 weeks as an approximation. In months with 5 working weeks, real pacing will be slightly lower than shown. For most agencies this is accurate enough; if you need day‑level precision, an integrated system is a better fit."},{"q":"How do I update dropdowns when I add a new person or project?","a":"In Excel: go to the Allocation sheet, select the column with the dropdown, Data → Data validation, and extend the list range. In Google Sheets: click the cell, dropdown icon, edit list. Names must match exactly those in the Team or Projects sheets."}]},{"id":"8150b074-f194-45d2-a3ea-f3e89f948672","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Summary: what changes with a well‑built template","anchorId":"resumen"},{"id":"85b3bcd9-d758-459b-860c-04813ae6b272","type":"paragraph","html":"The difference between an agency that “thinks it is doing fine” and one that knows it is usually lives in a handful of Excel columns: net capacity, assigned hours, utilization, pacing, and margin. It is not rocket science: it is data discipline, dropdowns so nothing breaks, protection so you do not overwrite what matters, and weekly review."},{"id":"3acc942c-1e15-4b53-850d-3168e57ba696","type":"paragraph","html":"When that discipline no longer scales with a sheet, the same logic can live in a tool that updates numbers passively. The criteria you have just learned do not expire; the medium you apply them in can evolve."},{"id":"b1e219b2-c018-497a-8d1f-8d540b6aae1d","type":"paragraph","html":"The KPIs that go with this template — utilization, pacing, estimated vs. actual — are covered in more depth inKPIs for marketing agencies. Time‑management that keeps tasks from expanding without control appears inParkinson’s Lawandtimeboxing. The global picture of schedule + budget + team comes together inproject planning."},{"id":"b983ed24-d5dd-4c02-8056-be2de2799d6e","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"The template is the first step; the planner is the next one","anchorId":"cta-final"},{"id":"70615774-3e94-4928-807b-16db0eab07b2","type":"paragraph","html":"Capacity, allocation, pacing, and utilization without maintaining the sheet by hand. You can explore Taimbox with no commitment."},{"id":"d1273dcd-f497-406a-9e07-a2393d90f9f0","type":"cta","text":"How Taimbox automates your template","href":"/planificador-recursos","variant":"primary"},{"id":"6b630263-f5dd-4974-9fe0-32b40a4da71f","type":"cta","text":"Download .xlsx template","href":"/reportes-rentabilidad","variant":"secondary"},{"id":"1c5449e0-da72-4095-a6e7-c7588a0b057a","type":"paragraph","html":"<em>Written by the Taimbox team — Resource management and profitability for agencies.</em>"},{"id":"6418f61a-9f0d-4208-a82a-0d17a92fdc5e","type":"relatedPost","slug":"planificacion-proyectos-cronograma-recursos"}]'::jsonb,
  json_ld_es = '{"@context":"https://schema.org","@graph":[{"@type":"Article","headline":"Plantilla gratuita de planificación de recursos para agencias","description":"Descarga nuestra plantilla de Excel/Google Sheets para gestionar la capacidad de tu equipo, el pacing de proyectos y el margen de tu agencia.","author":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"publisher":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"datePublished":"2026-03-24","inLanguage":"es","mainEntityOfPage":{"@type":"WebPage","@id":"https://taimbox.com/blog/plantilla-planificacion-recursos-agencia"}},{"@type":"FAQPage","mainEntity":[{"@type":"Question","name":"¿Necesito macros o VBA para que funcione la plantilla?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"No. Solo usa fórmulas estándar (SUMA, SI, SUMIF, VLOOKUP, SUMPRODUCT, COUNTIF) y formato condicional nativo. Funciona en Excel, LibreOffice y Google Sheets sin necesidad de habilitar macros."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"¿Cada cuánto hay que actualizar la plantilla?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Lo ideal es revisarla al inicio de cada semana (o al final de la anterior): ajustar ausencias en Equipo y añadir las asignaciones de la nueva semana. La frecuencia semanal da tiempo a reaccionar antes de que una sobrecarga se convierta en crisis."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"¿A partir de cuántas personas deja de ser práctico el Excel?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"No hay un número mágico; depende más del ritmo de cambios (proyectos nuevos, rotaciones) que del tamaño. En la práctica, muchas agencias notan la fricción entre 8 y 15 personas con múltiples proyectos simultáneos: ahí el mantenimiento semanal empieza a no compensar."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"¿Puedo usar esta plantilla junto a un tablero Kanban (Trello, Asana…)?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Sí: el Kanban gestiona el flujo de tareas; la plantilla de recursos gestiona horas y capacidad. Se complementan: el tablero dice «qué se está haciendo» y la plantilla dice «quién tiene horas libres para hacerlo»."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"¿Qué rango de utilización es «sano» en una agencia?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Orientativo: 70–85 % sobre capacidad neta en muchas agencias de servicios. Por debajo puede indicar falta de pipeline; por encima del 90 % empieza el riesgo de quemazo y errores. El mix de negocio (retainers, proyectos puntuales, I+D interna) cambia el objetivo."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"¿El pacing tiene en cuenta que no todos los meses duran lo mismo?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"La fórmula divide las horas presupuestadas entre 4 semanas como aproximación. En meses de 5 semanas laborales, el pacing real será ligeramente inferior al mostrado. Para la mayoría de agencias la aproximación es suficiente; si necesitas precisión al día, un sistema integrado lo resuelve mejor."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"¿Cómo actualizo los desplegables si añado una persona o proyecto nuevo?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"En Excel: ve a la hoja Asignación, selecciona la columna con el desplegable, Datos → Validación de datos, y amplía la lista. En Google Sheets: clic en la celda, icono de desplegable, editar lista. Los nombres deben coincidir exactamente con las hojas Equipo o Proyectos."}}]}]}'::jsonb,
  json_ld_en = '{"@context":"https://schema.org","@graph":[{"@type":"Article","headline":"Free agency resource planning template","description":"Download our Excel/Google Sheets template to manage your team''s capacity, project pacing, and agency margin.","author":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"publisher":{"@type":"Organization","name":"Taimbox"},"datePublished":"2026-03-24","inLanguage":"en","mainEntityOfPage":{"@type":"WebPage","@id":"https://taimbox.com/en/blog/agency-resource-planning-template"}},{"@type":"FAQPage","mainEntity":[{"@type":"Question","name":"Do I need macros or VBA for the template to work?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"No. It only uses standard formulas (SUM, IF, SUMIF, VLOOKUP, SUMPRODUCT, COUNTIF) and native conditional formatting. It works in Excel, LibreOffice, and Google Sheets without enabling macros."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"How often do I need to update the template?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Ideally at the start of each week (or the end of the previous one): adjust absences in the Team sheet and add allocations for the new week. Weekly cadence gives you time to react before overload turns into a crisis."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"From how many people does Excel stop being practical?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"There is no magic number; it depends more on the pace of change (new projects, staff changes) than on headcount. In practice many agencies feel the friction between roughly 8 and 15 people with several parallel projects: from that point on, weekly maintenance stops paying off."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Can I use this template alongside a Kanban board (Trello, Asana…)?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Yes. The board manages the flow of tasks; the resource template manages hours and capacity. They complement each other: the board tells you what is being worked on and the template tells you who has hours left to do it."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"What utilization range is “healthy” in an agency?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"As a rough guide, 70–85% of net capacity in many service agencies. Below that, you may have pipeline issues; above 90% you start to see burnout and errors. The ideal point depends on your mix of work (retainers, one‑off projects, internal R&D)."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"Does pacing account for months having different lengths?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"The formula divides budgeted hours by 4 weeks as an approximation. In months with 5 working weeks, real pacing will be slightly lower than shown. For most agencies this is accurate enough; if you need day‑level precision, an integrated system is a better fit."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"How do I update dropdowns when I add a new person or project?","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"In Excel: go to the Allocation sheet, select the column with the dropdown, Data → Data validation, and extend the list range. In Google Sheets: click the cell, dropdown icon, edit list. Names must match exactly those in the Team or Projects sheets."}}]}]}'::jsonb
WHERE slug = 'plantilla-planificacion-recursos-agencia';

-- gestion-carga-trabajo-equipo-sin-burnout